## TL;DR: Three Stone Cushion Cut Diamond Ring — What You Must Know First

**Most three stone cushion cut diamond rings at retail do NOT have cushion-shaped side stones — they use oval, half-moon, baguette, or trapezoid flankers because matching small cushions as side stones barely exist in production.** Choose your flanker shape before your setting; the flanker defines the ring's entire aesthetic more than the center stone's cut does. **→ Best first pick:** [IGI 1ct E-VVS2 Lab Cushion at ~$680](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Petite Three-Stone Lab-Grown 14K Rose Gold at $1,680](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-three-stone-lab-grown-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-rose-gold-item-309375?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **from $2,360 total**.

**Priority:** The center stone matters most — spend 60–70% of your budget there. The setting determines your flanker shape, and the flanker shape is the hardest decision in this category; half-moon flankers are the most harmonious with a cushion center, trapezoid flankers are the most dramatic, and tapered baguettes are the most traditional. A solitaire costs 15–25% less at equivalent stone quality but delivers none of the trilogy symbolism or the visual width that three stones create.

