## What Is a Three Stone Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

A three stone cushion cut diamond ring is an engagement ring featuring a cushion-cut center diamond flanked by two side stones — traditionally representing the past, present, and future of a relationship. The three-stone design dates to Georgian and Victorian jewelry as a narrative form of fine jewelry, but it was popularized globally after Prince Charles gave Princess Diana a three-stone sapphire ring in 1981. In its modern retail form, a three stone cushion ring is a build-your-own project: the buyer selects a certified center cushion diamond, then pairs it with a three-stone setting that determines the shape, size, and metal of the side stones.

The search intent for "three stone cushion cut diamond ring" splits across three buyer types: those comparing it to solitaires on value and visual impact, those looking for specific flanker configurations (trapezoids, half-moons, baguettes), and those deciding between lab and natural for the center stone. This guide answers all three, explains why The Flanker Problem is the single most important thing to understand before you buy, and provides complete stone-plus-setting builds at every budget from $2,360 to nearly $10,000. Every price in this guide links directly to Blue Nile with affiliate pricing.

The cushion cut became one of the most popular shapes for three-stone centers in {{year}} because its soft, rounded silhouette works harmoniously with most flanker shapes without creating the visual conflict that sharper-cornered shapes like princess or radiant sometimes create against curved side stones. Cushion cuts also deliver excellent finger coverage width relative to their carat weight — and adding side stones extends that width further. A 1ct cushion at 6.5mm with 0.35ct half-moon sides reaches a combined visual span approaching 10–11mm across the finger.

