## FAQs: Three Stone Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

### What side stones go with a cushion cut center in a three-stone ring?
Half-moon side stones are the most harmonious because their curved shape echoes the cushion's soft corner geometry. Trapezoid side stones offer the most dramatic geometric contrast. Tapered baguettes are the most traditional option, and oval flankers are the most elongating. True cushion-cut side stones to match a cushion center are virtually unavailable in mainstream retail — this is The Flanker Problem.

### Is a three stone cushion ring more expensive than a solitaire?
Yes, by approximately 15–25% at equivalent center stone quality. A solitaire concentrates the full budget into one center stone; a three-stone ring splits budget between center stone and setting, which includes pre-set side stones. At a $4,000 total budget, a solitaire can accommodate a larger or higher-quality cushion center than a three-stone ring at the same amount.

### What is the three stone cushion cut lab grown diamond price?
An IGI-certified 1ct E-VVS2 lab cushion starts at approximately $680 at Blue Nile in {{year}}. A 1.5ct lab cushion at E-VVS2 starts at approximately $1,200. Combined with a three-stone setting starting at $1,680, the entry build for a complete three-stone cushion cut lab grown diamond ring is from $2,360 total.

### How many carats should the center stone be in a three stone cushion ring?
For most retail three-stone settings calibrated for standard side stone sizes, a center cushion of 0.75ct–1.5ct gives the best visual proportion. A 1ct cushion at 6.5mm satisfies The Trio Width Rule with most pre-set side stone configurations. Under 0.75ct can look underpowered against the visual mass of two side stones; over 2ct requires verifying the setting's side stone dimensions scale correctly to the 1.5–2× width ratio.

### What is the difference between a trilogy ring and a three stone ring?
No difference in design — trilogy is the British and Australian term for the same ring style (center diamond flanked by two side diamonds). Both describe the same ring architecture; trilogy is regional naming used primarily in UK and Australian retail markets.

### What is the cushion flanked by trapezoids ring?
A cushion flanked by trapezoids ring features a cushion center with two trapezoidal step-cut side stones — wide at the top, narrowing toward the band, with a rectangular step-cut face. The Blue Nile [Three-Stone Trapezoid Sidestone 14K Rose Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-trapezoid-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-rose-gold-item-203681?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is priced at [$5,900](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-trapezoid-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-rose-gold-item-203681?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and creates the most Art Deco-influenced three-stone cushion ring available in this guide.

### What is the cushion half moon three stone ring?
A cushion half-moon three stone ring pairs a cushion-cut center diamond with two half-moon (D-shaped, brilliant-cut) side stones. The curved shape of the half-moon mirrors the cushion's soft corner geometry, making this the most visually cohesive flanker pairing for a cushion center. The Blue Nile [Three-Stone Half-Moon Sidestone 14K White Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-half-moon-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-item-203679?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is priced at [$5,320](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/three-stone-half-moon-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-item-203679?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

### Should I use yellow gold or white gold for a three stone cushion ring?
Yellow gold is preferred for G–H color center stones because it neutralizes any warmth in the diamond. White gold is preferred for D–F colorless centers to maximize brightness and contrast. Rose gold flatters G–H color centers similarly to yellow gold but reads as more romantic, pairing especially well with oval or half-moon flanker shapes.

### What does a complete three stone cushion cut diamond ring cost?
Entry lab builds start at $2,360 (IGI 1ct lab cushion + Petite Three-Stone RG setting). Natural builds start at $3,656 (GIA 1ct G-VS1 + Petite Micropavé Trio WG). High-end geometric builds with GIA 1.5ct natural centers range from $9,120 (half-moon) to $9,700 (trapezoid). All prices in this guide include both center stone and setting with pre-set side stones.

### Can I put a cushion cut diamond in any three stone setting?
Three-stone settings at Blue Nile accept cushion center stones within each setting's specified size range, typically 4mm–10mm across. Always verify the minimum and maximum center stone dimensions in millimeters for each setting before purchasing. Settings with very tight prong configurations or channel-set side stones may have narrower center stone size tolerances than open four-prong designs.

### What is The Trio Width Rule for a three stone cushion ring?
The Trio Width Rule states the center stone should be 1.5–2× wider than each side stone to maintain visual hierarchy. For a 1ct cushion at 6.5mm, ideal side stones are 3.25–4.3mm wide (roughly 0.25–0.50ct each). The center stone should also carry 55–65% of the ring's total diamond carat weight to read as the dominant focal point rather than sharing visual weight equally with the flankers.

### Is a three stone cushion ring worth it vs a solitaire?
Three stone cushion rings are worth the 15–25% premium over solitaires if visual finger coverage width, past-present-future symbolism, and photographic presence matter to you. They are not worth the premium if your goal is maximizing center stone size or quality at a fixed budget — solitaires accomplish that more efficiently. The three stone is the right ring when the story the ring tells matters; the solitaire is right when the single diamond is the entire statement.

### Does a three stone cushion ring cost more to resize?
Yes, more than a plain-band solitaire, though comparable to other styles with side stones. Settings with step-cut side stones (trapezoid, baguette) are the hardest to resize because the parallel face alignment of step cuts must be preserved during resizing. Oval and half-moon settings are easier because their cut shapes are more forgiving of minor prong repositioning.

